  "prompt": "What are some bad habits that self-taught programmers develop?",
  "response": "Here are some common bad habits that self-taught programmers might develop:\n\n1. Copy-Paste Coding\n- Relying too heavily on Stack Overflow solutions\n- Copying code without understanding it\n- Not comprehending the underlying principles\n\n2. Poor Code Organization\n- Lack of structured code\n- Minimal or no documentation\n- Inconsistent naming conventions\n- No separation of concerns\n\n3. Avoiding Best Practices\n- Not using version control (Git)\n- Skipping code reviews\n- Neglecting testing\n- Ignoring code refactoring\n\n4. Limited Learning Approach\n- Sticking to one programming language\n- Not exploring different programming paradigms\n- Not keeping up with industry trends\n- Avoiding challenging concepts\n\n5. Performance and Efficiency Issues\n- Writing inefficient algorithms\n- Not optimizing code\n- Lack of understanding of time and space complexity\n- Ignoring memory management\n\n6. Security Negligence\n- Weak input validation\n- Improper error handling\n- Not understanding security vulnerabilities\n- Hardcoding sensitive information\n\n7. Debugging Shortcuts\n- Relying too much on print statements\n- Not using proper debugging tools\n- Not systematically isolating issues\n\n8. Overconfidence\n- Not asking for help\n- Assuming first solution is always best\n- Resisting constructive criticism\n\n9. Technical Debt\n- Quick, hacky solutions\n- Postponing code improvements\n- Neglecting code quality",
